00:02:56.760 --> 00:03:00.040
Let's first ask,
what is an overlay?

00:03:00.040 --> 00:03:03.270
An overlay is a tool that
provides some accessibility

00:03:03.270 --> 00:03:07.590
or usability feature that may not
be built into the underlying site.

00:03:07.590 --> 00:03:10.460
Sometimes it replicates native
features and sometimes it offers

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:12.270
some other affordance.

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:15.150
Often does the work in the
end-user's browser relying

00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:17.480
on each user's computer
to replicate the same work

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:19.870
as every other user's computer.

00:03:19.870 --> 00:03:23.240
They can also be referred to as
widgets, toolbars, or add-ons.

00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:27.410
There were many tools that
predated native features

00:03:27.410 --> 00:03:30.000
or that were created to
fill gaps in technology,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.070
including assistive technology.

00:03:32.070 --> 00:03:34.990
Some techniques and standards
may not have been defined

00:03:34.990 --> 00:03:38.590
or even well-supported when
these tools were created.

00:03:38.590 --> 00:03:41.700
The risk is that these tools
required users to learn them anew

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:45.710
for every site with features that
would not carry across sites.

00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:50.740
This might be loud, I'm hoping not.

00:03:52.050 --> 00:03:54.060
BrowseAloud is an early example.

00:03:54.060 --> 00:03:56.090
It converts the text
on a page to speech.

00:03:56.090 --> 00:04:01.708
AI: Change Region, Product,
For Education, Read&Write,

00:04:02.309 --> 00:04:10.940
EquatIO, Speechstream, WriQ,
Fluency Tutor, OrbitNote.

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:13.186
For Work, Read&Write.

00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:18.200
<v Adrian> This as you can
see or hear offers no context

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:20.350
for what is being
read, visible or not.

00:04:20.350 --> 00:04:23.580
It was never meant to
replicate screen readers.

00:04:23.580 --> 00:04:26.930
Instead, it's akin to a feature you
can find built into browsers today,

00:04:26.930 --> 00:04:29.550
such as Edge's Immersive Reader.

00:04:29.550 --> 00:04:32.130
BrowserAloud requires a
third-party embedded script,

00:04:32.130 --> 00:04:35.920
and back in 2018 was briefly
hacked to mine cryptocurrencies.

00:04:37.572 --> 00:04:40.246
Some widgets made an effort
to replicate features already

00:04:40.247 --> 00:04:42.110
in browsers
and operating systems.

00:04:42.110 --> 00:04:45.660
These ranged from text sizing
to contrast and lightness,

00:04:45.660 --> 00:04:48.980
to motion control and even
zooming and magnification.

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:53.220
This text sizing widget
shows how they can go wrong,

00:04:53.220 --> 00:04:55.610
is no longer available on the site.

00:04:55.610 --> 00:04:57.820
Assuming you could find
it behind a gear icon,

00:04:57.820 --> 00:05:01.060
the control only appeared when
you were at the top of the page.

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:04.310
The widget only resized
article content, not headlines,

00:05:04.310 --> 00:05:06.630
not navigation, nothing else.

00:05:06.630 --> 00:05:09.220
Since that article content
was outside the viewport,

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:13.050
it also made it near impossible
to compare sizing options.

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:15.680
It does not retain the size
as you navigate the site

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:19.460
and when you return to the site
or even for the print styles.

00:05:19.460 --> 00:05:22.520
Better implementations have shown
users how to change their browser

00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:25.030
or operating systems instead.

00:05:25.030 --> 00:05:28.020
However, this could be a useful
stop-gap feature to gauge

00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:32.080
if users regularly scale text
and perhaps adjust those defaults

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:33.460
on your site as a result.

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:38.740
Some widgets exist because
there is no native equivalent

00:05:38.740 --> 00:05:43.260
or the needs are not well
represented in what exists.

00:05:43.260 --> 00:05:46.150
Success for those widgets comes
down to how well they perform.

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:49.760
Hand Talk is another add-on.

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:53.770
It will load an animated avatar
to sign the content of a page,

00:05:53.770 --> 00:05:56.880
like the text-to-speech example
earlier, it presents the content

00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:59.050
of the page in sign language.

00:05:59.050 --> 00:06:01.061
It still cannot offer
the same context

00:06:01.062 --> 00:06:02.660
for what content is associated

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:06.690
with what other content, so the
user may need to also read along.

00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:11.070
I did not explore how many
sign languages it supports.

00:06:11.070 --> 00:06:13.328
To its credit,
it is not finger-spelling everything

00:06:13.329 --> 00:06:17.050
it encounters, but I leave it to
the audience to judge its value.

00:06:19.960 --> 00:06:21.614
The current list of
overlay vendors is

00:06:21.615 --> 00:06:23.140
not necessarily filling these gaps,

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:26.870
however, they are capitalizing on
a general lack of understanding

00:06:26.870 --> 00:06:30.060
of people and needs,
focusing on selling quick fixes

00:06:30.060 --> 00:06:31.960
to businesses instead.

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:37.250
These companies include AccessiBe,
AccessiWay, Adally, AudioEye,

00:06:37.250 --> 00:06:43.450
redacted, FACIL'iti, MaxAccess,
Poloda AI, Purple Lens, redacted,

00:06:43.450 --> 00:06:44.860
and UserWay.

00:06:44.860 --> 00:06:47.520
There are also vendors that
white-label some of these products.

00:06:49.310 --> 00:06:52.090
Overlays tend to
overstate their abilities.

00:06:52.090 --> 00:06:54.860
In technical reviews,
they consistently underperform.

00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:59.470
Automated accessibility
testing tools are not perfect,

00:06:59.470 --> 00:07:01.140
but we can use them
to get a sense of

00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:05.490
whether or not an overlay has
improved WCAG compliance of the page.

00:07:05.490 --> 00:07:08.560
I used an automated checker to
compare the number of errors before

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:11.120
and after an overlay was activated.

00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:14.600
The page had more detectable
WCAG errors after.

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:16.870
The examples that follow
are about a year old.

00:07:16.870 --> 00:07:19.520
I opted not to retest
because I have no interest

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:21.510
in providing free testing.

00:07:21.510 --> 00:07:24.970
Besides, these vendors were claiming
WCAG compliance when I tested.

00:07:24.970 --> 00:07:28.470
If they were lying then, there's no
reason to assume they would stop now.

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:34.410
Deque's Axe browser plugin prides
itself on no false positives.

00:07:34.410 --> 00:07:38.120
As a result, it may be more lenient
than a human tester would be.

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:41.230
After running an overlay on the
vendor's own page, the number

00:07:41.230 --> 00:07:45.750
of detectable errors identified
by Axe tripled, from 4 to 12.

00:07:47.310 --> 00:07:51.410
TPGI's ARC toolkit plugin is
less likely to be lenient.

00:07:51.410 --> 00:07:55.050
When testing the same page, the
number of detectable errors doubled,

00:07:55.050 --> 00:07:58.060
jumping from 19 to 38 when
the overlay was activated.

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:04.330
ARC also jumped from
164 warnings to 193.

00:08:04.330 --> 00:08:06.680
These do not represent
clear WCAG violations,

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:08.900
but instead warrant some
form of manual testing.

00:08:10.590 --> 00:08:13.870
WebAIM's WAVE checker browser
plugin returned no violations

00:08:13.870 --> 00:08:15.820
without the overlay active.

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:19.370
After the overlay was activated,
a single contrast violation appeared.

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:23.290
I've written about my concerns
at AccessiBe was spoofing WAVE,

00:08:23.290 --> 00:08:26.630
though I cannot wade into
that code to confirm this.

00:08:26.630 --> 00:08:31.580
WAVE used to display a message, "The
third party AccessiBe integration

00:08:31.580 --> 00:08:36.290
on this page may temporarily modify
content when WAVE is activated,

00:08:36.290 --> 00:08:38.380
resulting in interference
with WAVE detection

00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:42.110
of/and accuracy identifying
accessibility and compliance issues."

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:49.070
We know that automated accessibility
testing tools only identify

00:08:49.070 --> 00:08:51.320
about 30% of issues.

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:53.950
That number shifts based on
complexity and other factors.

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:57.130
That 30% number
acknowledges that much

00:08:57.130 --> 00:09:01.270
of WCAG requires human
judgment based on context.

00:09:01.270 --> 00:09:04.920
Overlay vendors claim they
can address the other 70%.

00:09:04.920 --> 00:09:06.590
That is a bold claim.

00:09:06.590 --> 00:09:08.150
It is also easy to disprove.

00:09:10.210 --> 00:09:12.900
The stop animations button
on this overlay fails

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:15.640
to stop the auto-playing
background video.

00:09:15.640 --> 00:09:19.290
To compound the confusion, the button
changes only its accessible name

00:09:19.290 --> 00:09:21.500
when pressed,
it does not use aria-press

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:22.970
to indicate it has been activated.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:27.420
That brief flash you saw was simply
from the YouTube video looping.

00:09:30.470 --> 00:09:33.490
I tried the keyboard navigation
feature of one vendor

00:09:33.490 --> 00:09:38.820
since its unaddressed navigation
violates 1.4.13 content on hover

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:41.910
and 2.4.7 focus visible.

00:09:41.910 --> 00:09:45.880
Even after I activate the feature,
focus styles are still missing.

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:49.280
Eventually, a new box
appears with different links.

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:50.580
I was tapping so much already.

00:09:50.580 --> 00:09:54.170
I tapped past the item that
displayed the instructions.

00:09:54.170 --> 00:09:58.000
To drive home the point, it drops
me into a de facto keyboard trap

00:09:58.000 --> 00:09:59.000
and it's cookie popup.

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:05.450
It's not just the claimed
fixes that do not work.

00:10:05.450 --> 00:10:08.370
The tools themselves
present barriers.

00:10:08.370 --> 00:10:11.370
The button in the background
video is one example.

00:10:11.370 --> 00:10:14.370
In other cases, screen reader
users have noted they hear sounds

00:10:14.370 --> 00:10:16.690
from the overlay with no
explanation what they mean.

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:20.100
The tools don't even
prevent their own customer

00:10:20.100 --> 00:10:21.980
from making new WCAG violations.

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:25.159
Here, the overlay is very tall,

00:10:25.160 --> 00:10:27.600
so this image captures
four screen fulls.

00:10:27.600 --> 00:10:31.900
It shows how the contrast of the
controls is so light, it is hard

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:35.850
to determine if one is active
or at what degree it is active.

00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:38.890
Some of the text and
icons are illegible.

00:10:38.890 --> 00:10:42.320
The language selector, which
commits the internationalization sin

00:10:42.320 --> 00:10:46.030
of using flags to choose language,
provides no alt attributes

00:10:46.030 --> 00:10:47.680
for those flags.

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:51.360
The overlay violates at least
three WCAG success criteria

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:53.140
from just a few
seconds of examination.

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:56.850
Part of this is because
the configuration options

00:10:56.850 --> 00:10:59.410
for the overlay customer
do not prevent them

00:10:59.410 --> 00:11:02.890
from choosing colors that
clearly fail contrast checks.

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:06.040
Here, the white text on the pink
white background has a contrast ratio

00:11:06.040 --> 00:11:07.870
of 1.2 to 1.

00:11:07.870 --> 00:11:10.630
The overlay vendor allowed
its customer to do this.

00:11:13.670 --> 00:11:17.410
Here, we can see that the browser's
default focus ring is active,

00:11:17.410 --> 00:11:19.390
but then the browser
alert prompting the user

00:11:19.390 --> 00:11:21.950
to activate the overlay appears.

00:11:21.950 --> 00:11:25.590
If the user declines,
that focus ring is somehow removed.

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:30.790
The only clue that focus is changing
is in the browser status bar

00:11:30.790 --> 00:11:33.310
or when the page eventually
jumps to scroll down.

00:11:37.010 --> 00:11:40.840
Here, I navigate an overlay vendor
site and as the new page was loading,

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:43.490
it grazed itself as if
a model will appear,

00:11:43.490 --> 00:11:45.700
and then some hidden
audio starts playing.

00:11:47.207 --> 00:11:47.960
<v Ronnie> Hi.

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:51.990
I'm Ronnie from AccessiBe,
