to the standard of the World
Wide Web Consortium, W3C,

00:15:21.460 --> 00:15:24.540
without any errors
or validation warning

00:15:24.540 --> 00:15:26.980
in W3C's troubleshooting
inspections.

00:15:28.090 --> 00:15:30.790
Please note that licensee
changes to such website

00:15:30.790 --> 00:15:33.850
may impact the functionality
of the service.

00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:38.000
By way of example, AccessiBe systems
do not support other components

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.120
such as Canvas, Flash, and/or SVG."

00:15:43.760 --> 00:15:46.680
Essentially, AccessiBe states
that its customer websites

00:15:46.680 --> 00:15:50.770
must already meet the
standard, which we confirmed is

00:15:50.770 --> 00:15:56.520
defined as WCAG 2.1 AA with no errors
or even warnings from the validator.

00:15:58.220 --> 00:16:01.640
Again, essentially your site
must be WCAG compliant to conform

00:16:01.640 --> 00:16:05.380
to AccessiBe's terms for
a product guaranteeing

00:16:05.380 --> 00:16:06.910
to make your site WCAG-compliant.

00:16:07.920 --> 00:16:11.550
AccessiBe then goes on to
exempt PDFs, Flash, SVG files,

00:16:11.550 --> 00:16:16.090
and even any mobile devices not
running Android 8 or iOS 10.

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:22.430
To remind you that AccessiBe is not
the only one making these claims,

00:16:22.430 --> 00:16:24.310
here is UserWay site.

00:16:24.310 --> 00:16:28.450
It says it will make your site
ADA-compliant, which is not a thing.

00:16:28.450 --> 00:16:31.380
It brags about the lack
of lawsuits mentioning it.

00:16:31.380 --> 00:16:35.010
It claims to have a strong reputation
in the disability community.

00:16:35.010 --> 00:16:38.480
It asserts its privacy chops
and it claims it is secured

00:16:38.480 --> 00:16:40.410
by not tracking people
with disabilities.

00:16:42.670 --> 00:16:44.750
I do not have a Lexus
Nexus subscription

00:16:44.750 --> 00:16:47.670
to confirm UserWay's
claim about lawsuits,

00:16:47.670 --> 00:16:50.070
but I know Yieldstreet
was unable to use UserWay

00:16:50.070 --> 00:16:51.820
to get its lawsuit dismissed.

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:57.170
However, I can say that many lawsuits
do not name the overlay vendor.

00:16:57.170 --> 00:16:59.500
Many of these vendors claim
they can protect their customers

00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:00.820
from lawsuits.

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:02.989
AccessiBe's CEO has even written

00:17:02.989 --> 00:17:06.570
"Never not once had
encountered a company

00:17:06.570 --> 00:17:11.330
that got sued because of
AccessiBe." Yet in 2020,

00:17:11.330 --> 00:17:15.840
over 250 companies were sued
after investing in overlays.

00:17:15.840 --> 00:17:19.650
The lawsuit pace picked up to almost
one per day by the end of the year.

00:17:21.610 --> 00:17:23.010
Here are just five examples.

00:17:23.010 --> 00:17:25.840
At least one of which
mentioned the vendor by name.

00:17:25.840 --> 00:17:29.040
Four of them mentioned AccessiBe
despite its CEO's claims.

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:34.230
They are Kolesar v.
ByIt, LLC, Thomas Klaus

00:17:34.230 --> 00:17:37.550
and Robert Jahoda v.
Upright Technologies, Blair

00:17:37.550 --> 00:17:43.030
Douglas v. Masterbuilt Manufacturing,
LLC, Murphy v. Eyebobs, LLC,

00:17:44.370 --> 00:17:49.430
Fischler et al v. Dorai Homes,
and LightHouse et al v. ADP.

00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:55.650
The LightHouse-ADP case goes
further and explicitly states that

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:00.250
"For the purpose of this
agreement, overlay solutions

00:18:00.250 --> 00:18:04.030
such as those currently provided
by companies such as AudioEye

00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:08.090
and AccessiBe will not suffice
to achieve accessibility."

00:18:11.810 --> 00:18:14.760
The Eyebobs case concluded in
a settlement where Eyebobs has

00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:17.800
to create an accessibility
team, perform an audit,

00:18:17.800 --> 00:18:21.930
adopt a policy statement,
implement an accessibility strategy

00:18:21.930 --> 00:18:24.420
and provide accessibility training.

00:18:24.420 --> 00:18:26.310
The overlay did not
protect Eyebobs.

00:18:27.760 --> 00:18:32.560
WIRED wrote an article titled This
Company Tapped AI for its Website

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:33.560
and Landed in Court.

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:36.870
I'm going to read a bit
from the article now.

00:18:38.230 --> 00:18:40.520
"In a statement,
AccessiBe's head of Marketing.

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:44.620
Gil Magen, said the company
had analyzed Eyebobs' website

00:18:44.620 --> 00:18:47.610
and found it complied with
the accessibility standards.

00:18:47.610 --> 00:18:50.550
AccessiBe offers clients
assistance with litigations,

00:18:50.550 --> 00:18:53.310
but Eyebobs declined,
the statement said.

00:18:53.310 --> 00:18:56.440
In its own statement, Eyebobs
said AccessiBe failed to respond

00:18:56.440 --> 00:18:58.390
to request for meetings
with its lawyers.

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:03.600
'Eyebobs is no longer working with
AccessiBe nor will we in the future."

00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:04.760
the statement said.

00:19:08.150 --> 00:19:10.990
Sometimes a company relies on
the overlay as its only way

00:19:10.990 --> 00:19:13.990
to become accessible to
customers, but what happens

00:19:13.990 --> 00:19:15.980
when the script will not load?

00:19:15.980 --> 00:19:17.630
Malwarebytes has blocked them.

00:19:17.630 --> 00:19:19.290
Ad blockers have blocked them.

00:19:19.290 --> 00:19:22.700
Firefox-enhanced privacy
protection blocks them.

00:19:22.700 --> 00:19:25.910
What if the script has an
error or the network chunks?

00:19:25.910 --> 00:19:27.670
Is your site "protected"?

00:19:29.030 --> 00:19:30.030
Are the users helped?

00:19:32.310 --> 00:19:34.610
This screenshot of
browser dev tools shows

00:19:34.610 --> 00:19:37.160
that the overlay
script has not loaded.

00:19:37.160 --> 00:19:40.180
Worse, that accessibility link
in the footer is just a div

00:19:40.180 --> 00:19:42.310
with a tab index and a button roll.

00:19:42.310 --> 00:19:43.820
It does nothing else when clicked

00:19:43.821 --> 00:19:45.650
because the overlay
script is supposed

00:19:45.650 --> 00:19:47.040
to replace it with a real control.

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:52.430
On the Malwarebytes' forum,
a user wanted to know if the script

00:19:52.430 --> 00:19:55.240
from an overlay vendor
was a tracker or not.

00:19:55.240 --> 00:19:58.680
The Malwarebytes staff
acknowledged it had been blocked.

00:19:58.680 --> 00:20:02.800
Until the user asked the question,
Malwarebytes had blocked the overlay

00:20:02.800 --> 00:20:05.560
for all its customers
for potentially years.

00:20:11.290 --> 00:20:14.040
The claims of no privacy
risk are spurious at best.

00:20:15.060 --> 00:20:18.920
Data Protection Impact
Assessment or DPIA is a process

00:20:18.920 --> 00:20:23.290
to help you identify and minimize the
data protection risks of a project.

00:20:23.290 --> 00:20:26.480
You must do a DPIA for processing
information that is likely

00:20:26.480 --> 00:20:29.400
to result in a high
risk to individuals.

00:20:29.400 --> 00:20:31.460
The vendors do not provide one.

00:20:31.460 --> 00:20:36.010
As a result, any claimed GDPR
compliance is in question.

00:20:36.010 --> 00:20:38.950
Remember that these overlay
scripts must parse all the content

00:20:38.950 --> 00:20:41.440
on the page, essentially
reading what you are surfing.

00:20:42.520 --> 00:20:44.660
Some of them keep your
settings from site to site

00:20:44.660 --> 00:20:45.810
by setting tracking cookies.

00:20:47.430 --> 00:20:49.780
Here in a tweet,
Léonie Watson demonstrates

00:20:49.780 --> 00:20:52.380
how cavalierly overly vendors
treat this compliance.

00:20:53.710 --> 00:20:56.710
The tweet, "Hello, AccessiBe.

00:20:56.710 --> 00:20:59.140
I've asked you by DM
and by phone for a copy

00:20:59.140 --> 00:21:00.726
of your Data Protection
Impact Assessment

00:21:00.726 --> 00:21:02.580
and you have not responded.

00:21:02.580 --> 00:21:05.580
Since asking discreetly has not
worked, I am now asking openly

00:21:05.580 --> 00:21:09.780
for you to share your DPIA since
you claim GDPR conformance.

00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:10.780
Thank you."

00:21:11.710 --> 00:21:15.430
She asked on April 1st, 2021,
and is still not heard back

00:21:15.430 --> 00:21:16.740
and it has been more than a year.

00:21:17.850 --> 00:21:20.350
I'm not a lawyer,
but this might be a GDPR violation.

00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:27.080
The DSW site uses redacted
assistive overlay.

00:21:27.080 --> 00:21:29.520
Though instead of an
accessibility icon in the corner,

00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:33.325
it uses the text
"Enable Accessibility"

00:21:33.325 --> 00:21:36.499
in gray on gray
located in the header.

00:21:36.500 --> 00:21:39.560
If you block third-party cookies,
you get the following browser alert

00:21:39.560 --> 00:21:40.600
when you try to activate it.

00:21:41.790 --> 00:21:45.390
An embedded page at
A40.redacted.com says

00:21:45.390 --> 00:21:48.780
your web browser privacy settings
are preventing the accessibility mode

00:21:48.780 --> 00:21:50.510
to stay enabled.

00:21:50.510 --> 00:21:54.360
Try enabling third-party cookies to
ensure you receive accessible updates

00:21:54.360 --> 00:21:55.360
to the website.

00:21:56.440 --> 00:21:58.800
This presents a false
choice between security

00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:01.990
and what may be a more
accessible experience.

00:22:01.990 --> 00:22:04.750
Nowhere does the user have
the opportunity to understand

00:22:04.750 --> 00:22:07.290
how those third-party
cookies will be used,

00:22:07.290 --> 00:22:08.690
what information will be shared.

00:22:10.140 --> 00:22:13.660
Essentially, a user has to disclose
a disability or access need

00:22:13.660 --> 00:22:16.650
with no indication how that
information will persist.

00:22:17.730 --> 00:22:19.780
It is also a reminder that
these products don't make

00:22:19.780 --> 00:22:27.170
a site more accessible, instead
these products make your computer try

00:22:27.170 --> 00:22:28.540
to make a site less broken.

00:22:31.130 --> 00:22:34.155
In August 2022, the Federal
Trade Commission announced

00:22:34.155 --> 00:22:37.456
an advanced notice of proposed
rule-making for a rule

00:22:37.456 --> 00:22:39.990
on commercial surveillance
and data security.

00:22:40.940 --> 00:22:43.960
I left the comment specifically
about the non-HIPAA health data

00:22:43.960 --> 00:22:46.780
to which overlays have
access, along with my concern

00:22:46.780 --> 00:22:49.170
that they can sell
it to data brokers.

00:22:49.170 --> 00:22:54.850
Since 99.98% of Americans can be
identified from an anonymized dataset

00:22:54.850 --> 00:22:59.320
with only 15 data points,
this should be a genuine concern.

00:22:59.320 --> 00:23:01.580
I hope the FTC treats it as such.

00:23:04.610 --> 00:23:07.930
Overlay vendors will over-promise
in their marketing, making claims

00:23:07.930 --> 00:23:11.060
about their utility and popularity
while under-delivering on them.

00:23:12.330 --> 00:23:16.090
These vendors rely on a combination
of fear, uncertainty, and doubt.

00:23:16.090 --> 00:23:20.210
They know how many website owners do
not understand accessibility laws.

00:23:20.210 --> 00:23:22.660
Even as users complain about the
problems with these products,

00:23:22.660 --> 00:23:25.220
the vendors use astroturfing
techniques to drown it out.

00:23:26.660 --> 00:23:29.780
This is an advertisement for
one of the overlay vendors.

00:23:29.780 --> 00:23:32.320
It is a cartoon of a man at
computer happily exclaiming,

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:34.290
"Finally, my website is up."

00:23:34.290 --> 00:23:37.320
Two men in suits suddenly appear
next to him holding legal papers

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:38.810
and say, "Not so fast.

00:23:38.810 --> 00:23:40.800
Nice website,
but it's not accessible.

00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:42.480
You've been served."

00:23:42.480 --> 00:23:45.450
The website owner now crying,
hands up in the air says,

00:23:45.450 --> 00:23:47.550
"I'm broke now, why bother?"

00:23:47.550 --> 00:23:50.560
In the background, the two men can
be seen walking away carrying bags

00:23:50.560 --> 00:23:51.560
of money.

00:23:52.230 --> 00:23:55.760
Overlay vendors use fear of
lawsuits to sell their product,

00:23:55.760 --> 00:23:57.600
not a desire to help users.

00:23:57.600 --> 00:24:00.620
The cartoon is careful not to show
disabled people as the villains,

00:24:00.620 --> 00:24:02.440
but the implication is clear.

00:24:02.440 --> 00:24:05.550
The laws that protect disabled
people will cost you money

00:24:05.550 --> 00:24:06.960
unless you pay for
the vendor's help.

00:24:09.690 --> 00:24:14.050
One vendor cited that a
"silent majority" of users

00:24:14.050 --> 00:24:16.160
like the overlay product
and that as a result,

00:24:16.160 --> 00:24:19.960
the complaints that appear
online are only exceptions.

00:24:19.960 --> 00:24:20.580
Here are Chancey.

00:24:20.580 --> 00:24:21.790
Fleet tweets.

00:24:21.790 --> 00:24:24.790
"The founders of AccessiBe are
interpreting the complacency

00:24:24.790 --> 00:24:29.090
of non-disabled customers and the
bone-deep fatigue of disabled users

00:24:29.090 --> 00:24:33.510
to mean that a silent majority,
their actual words, is grateful for

00:24:33.510 --> 00:24:36.720
and enjoys AccessiBe.

00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:37.810
Let's not be silent then."

00:24:39.220 --> 00:24:42.730
That was in reply to a tweet
from Marco Salsiccia who says,

00:24:42.730 --> 00:24:45.420
"Pretty much, as well as citing
their silent majority of blind users

00:24:45.420 --> 00:24:49.670
who approve and test their
product, I ran into so many issues

00:24:49.670 --> 00:24:51.960
just going through their
example sites alone.

00:24:51.960 --> 00:24:53.940
I didn't want to give
them a fully free audit

00:24:53.940 --> 00:24:55.370
of how much they were doing wrong."

00:24:57.840 --> 00:25:01.100
In addition, these vendors have a
history of astroturfing review sites,

00:25:01.100 --> 00:25:03.870
social media and
the web In general.

00:25:03.870 --> 00:25:07.910
The effort is to ensure
only their message appears,

00:25:07.910 --> 00:25:11.050
and they have the money SEO chops
and lack of integrity to do it.

00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:14.400
I have links to Twitter
spam, medium articles,

00:25:14.400 --> 00:25:17.600
paid promotion pieces and industry
sites, questionable reviews

00:25:17.600 --> 00:25:20.640
on other platforms, even Wikipedia
entries that were flagged

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:23.110
by the moderators as spam.

00:25:23.110 --> 00:25:25.460
The image here shows a
headline from WP Tavern

00:25:25.460 --> 00:25:30.680
when one vendor had all the fake
reviews for its plugin removed.

00:25:33.160 --> 00:25:36.130
In addition to individual complaints,
there has been press coverage

00:25:36.130 --> 00:25:37.660
of these companies.

00:25:37.660 --> 00:25:40.420
Users with some standing in the
disability community have spoken

00:25:40.420 --> 00:25:43.000
about overlay failures in general.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:45.978
Some users are so frustrated
they share tips and tools

00:25:45.978 --> 00:25:47.350
to block overlays.

00:25:47.350 --> 00:25:49.740
Two vendors have even
threatened users with lawsuits.

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:54.710
NBC News ran a story with
the headline Blind People,

00:25:54.710 --> 00:25:58.910
Advocates Slam Company Claiming
to Make Websites ADA Compliant.

00:25:59.970 --> 00:26:02.450
Vice also ran an
article headlined People

00:26:02.450 --> 00:26:05.980
With Disabilities Say This AI Tool
is Making the Web Worse for Them.

00:26:07.380 --> 00:26:10.030
The New York Times published
one over the summer,

00:26:10.030 --> 00:26:13.090
For Blind Internet Users,
the Fix Can Be Worse Than the Flaws.

00:26:14.720 --> 00:26:18.210
The Mosen At Large podcast devoted
an entire episode to the question

00:26:18.210 --> 00:26:20.090
of the value of overlays.

00:26:20.090 --> 00:26:24.100
Episode 105 asked, "Can AI
make the web fully accessible

00:26:24.100 --> 00:26:27.270
in a few short years,
or might it make matters worse?"

00:26:28.310 --> 00:26:31.250
A chunk of a follow-up episode
was devoted to more frustrations

00:26:31.250 --> 00:26:32.360
from users.

00:26:32.360 --> 00:26:34.900
Other community podcasts have
discussed these tools as well.

00:26:36.510 --> 00:26:39.610
Some users are so frustrated
that they have written tools

00:26:39.610 --> 00:26:41.400
to block overlays.

00:26:41.400 --> 00:26:45.110
Accessibegone gives instructions
for how to block overlays

00:26:45.110 --> 00:26:48.150
using ad blockers or by
editing your host file.

